# Same-line guard clauses

When an `if` body is a single guard statement (`throw …;`, `return;`, `return <expr>;`, `continue;`, `break;`), put it on the **same line** as the `if`, with no braces—including **`if (predicate) return result;`** when the **whole assembled line** is still readable (team tooling uses **≤ 160** characters for auto-collapse; shorten condition or hoist a local if it blows past that).

## Preferred

```csharp
if (key is null) throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(key));
if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(key)) return;
if (tenant is null) return null;
if (!TryParse(span, out int n)) return false;
if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(key)) continue;
if (cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested) return Task.CompletedTask;
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid — use single-line guards when readability allows
if (key is null)
{
    throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(key));
}

// Avoid — use: if (!TryParse(span, out int n)) return false;
if (!TryParse(span, out int n))
    return false;

// Avoid — use: if (tenant is null) return null;
if (tenant is null)
{
    return null;
}
```
## Scope

- Body must be **one** statement and must be a guard (early exit) — `throw`, `return`, `continue`, `break`, `goto`.
- Keep the **blank line before** the `if` per the project blank-line rule, **except** when the guard is the very first statement of the member or block.
- Keeps the eye on the **happy path** below the guards.
- Companion to **`SingleLineThrowNoBraces.mdc`**, **`SingleLineContinueNoBraces.mdc`**, **`CSharp-EmbeddedStatements-NoBraces.mdc`**, **`CSharp-SingleEmbeddedStatement-OneLinePrefer.mdc`** (general one-line embedding + length heuristic).
